ast Peckham, Kent, England":"East Peckham, Kent, England","Baddington, Cheshire, England":"Baddington, Cheshire, England","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"1395–1430":"1395–1430","1385–1468":"1385–1468","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1392–1433":"1392–1433","1400–1430":"1400–1430","1392–1432":"1392–1432","1408–1434":"1408–1434","1409–1488":"1409–1488","1376–1419":"1376–1419","1376–1482":"1376–1482","1385":"1385","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","4 Sep 1419":"4 September 1419","1468":"1468","1434":"1434","1488":"1488","1400":"1400","1433":"1433","1432":"1432","1376":"1376","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","East Peckham, Kent, England":"East Peckham, Kent, England","Baddington, Cheshire, England":"Baddington, Cheshire, England","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bromley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Bromley, in Essex, Hertfordshire, Kent (now in Greater London), Greater London, Greater Manchester, Staffordshire, Shropshire, and elsewhere. Most are named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, but Bromley (near Bow) in Greater London is from Old English <i>bræmbel</i> ‘bramble’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Brimley","meanings":["habitational name, perhaps from Brimley in Devon or Brimbley in Stoke Abbott, Dorset, both named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","variant of   Bromley  .","English:"]},{"name":"Brumley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bromley  . This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Bromley was born in 1395, in Baddington, Cheshire, England, his father, John de Bromley, was 19 and his mother, Agnes Trentham, was 19. He married Margery Mainwaring in 1409, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1430, in his hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1395–1430":"1395–1430","1385–1468":"1385–1468","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1392–1433":"1392–1433","1400–1430":"1400–1430","1392–1432":"1392–1432","1408–1434":"1408–1434","1409–1488":"1409–1488","1376–1419":"1376–1419","1376–1482":"1376–1482","1385":"1385","1395":"1395","1482":"1482","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","4 Sep 1419":"4. september 1419","1468":"1468","1434":"1434","1488":"1488","1400":"1400","1433":"1433","1432":"1432","1376":"1376","1430":"1430",